<paragraph blockId="16.[125,245,393,417]" box="[125,245,393,417]" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">
<emphasis box="[125,245,393,417]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[125,1173,442,817]" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">
Colonies erect, branched, shoots 
<quantity box="[527,642,442,466]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="mm" value="10.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="5.0">5–15 mm</quantity>
, monosiphonic, composed of main axis and shorter side-branches. Erect parts segmented by alternately oblique nodes; nodes distinct, internodes about 
<quantity box="[333,476,506,530]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="mm" value="0.55" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.6 mm</quantity>
long, diameter 
<quantity box="[665,788,504,530]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="mm" value="85.0" valueMax="90.0" valueMin="80.0">80–90 mm</quantity>
. Perisarc smooth. Side-branches originate from hydrophores. Hydrotheca near segment end, on very short hydrophore; hydrotheca does not reach beyond level of node. Primary hydrotheca with straight or slightly curved walls, basal diameter 
<quantity box="[546,721,601,625]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="mm" value="0.11" valueMax="0.12" valueMin="0.1">0.10–0.12 mm</quantity>
, depth 
<quantity box="[806,928,600,626]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="mm" value="25.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="20.0">20–30 mm</quantity>
, desmocytes present. Hydrophore without pseudodiaphragm. Secondary hydrotheca on corrugated hydrophore of variable length, several times longer than primary hydrophore. Gonothecae on main stem. Female gonotheca 
<quantity box="[426,568,697,721]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.499999999999999" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="mm" value="0.6499999999999999" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.7 mm</quantity>
long and about 
<quantity box="[773,865,697,721]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
broad, main body ovoid, bilaterally symmetric through a lateral hydrotheca that overtops gonotheca body, with crease-line running from hydrotheca along gonotheca body. Male gonothecae without hydrotheca, club-shaped, slightly curved or not, length 
<quantity box="[775,937,793,817]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.25" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="mm" value="0.525" valueMax="0.55" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.55 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[125,374,873,897]" box="[125,374,873,897]" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">
<emphasis box="[125,374,873,897]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">Additional information</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[125,1172,922,978]" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">
Stems may reach 
<quantity box="[330,388,922,946]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
in height. Female gonotheca with two hydranths (
<bibRefCitation author="Motz-Kossowska S" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" pagination="325 - 352" refId="ref15377" refString="Motz-Kossowska S. 1911. Contribution a la connaissance des hydraires de la Mediterranee occidentale: II, Hydraires calyptoblastiques. Archives de Zoologie Experimentale et Generale 6: 325 - 352." type="journal article" year="1911">Motz-Kossowska 1911</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[125,206,1035,1059]" box="[125,206,1035,1059]" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">
<emphasis box="[125,206,1035,1059]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">Biology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[125,1172,1083,1171]" pageId="16" pageNumber="622">
Depth range 
<quantity box="[277,384,1083,1107]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.005" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.01" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" unit="m" value="100.5" valueMax="200.0" valueMin="1.0">1–200 m</quantity>
, grows on a variety of solid substrata. Fertile colonies observed from June to October (
<bibRefCitation author="Pena Cantero AL &amp; Garcia Carrascosa AM" box="[340,867,1115,1139]" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" pagination="1 - 180" refId="ref15725" refString="Pena Cantero AL, Garcia Carrascosa AM. 2002. The benthic hydroid fauna of the Chafarinas Islands (Alboran Sea, western Mediterranean). Zoologische Verhandelingen 337: 1 - 180." type="journal article" year="2002">Peña Cantero and García Carrascosa 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Ecological aspects were investigated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Coma R &amp; Llobet I &amp; Zabala M &amp; Gili J-M &amp; Hughes RG" box="[308,538,1147,1171]" pageId="16" pageNumber="622" pagination="161 - 169" refId="ref14018" refString="Coma R, Llobet I, Zabala M, Gili J-M, Hughes RG. 1992. The population dynamics of Halecium petrosum and Halecium pusillum (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria), epiphytes of Halimeda tuna in the northwestern Mediterranean. Scientia Marina 56: 161 - 169." type="journal article" year="1992">Coma et al. (1992)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
